# redteam-loop — TODO

> Working backlog for petesherratt-collab/redteam-loop.
> **What this is:** A small, dependency-free multi-agent adversarial loop. A *proposer* drafts; a *red team* of adversary models (Gemini, GPT/Codex) attacks; critiques feed back into the next draft, for N rounds or until every adversary returns `VERDICT: PASS`. Transcripts saved to `runs/`. Reachable via OpenRouter (one key) or local vendor CLIs (Claude/Gemini/Codex). MIT.
> Status markers: `[ ]` open · `[~]` in progress · `[x]` done · `[!]` blocked.
> Last reviewed: 2026-06-26

---

## 0. Current state

Healthy, complete, well-documented — the cleanest README of the repo set. `orchestrate.mjs` (~11kb, dependency-free), three agent configs (`local`, `openrouter`, `cli`), LICENSE present. No hardcoded secrets seen. This is a *working tool*, so the backlog below is mostly hardening and reach, not repair.

## 1. Model slugs — verify before trusting a run (the one likely break)

- [ ] **All pinned slugs may be stale.** Configs reference `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.5`, `google/gemini-2.5-pro`, `openai/gpt-5`. If OpenRouter has retired/renamed any, that agent silently fails mid-loop. Confirm each ID still resolves at openrouter.ai/models; update the three configs if not.
  - Note: this is the **third repo** pinning `claude-sonnet-4.5` (also DE-site2, and the Salon pins `4-6`). See the cross-repo note in REPO-INDEX — worth standardising one current slug everywhere.
- [ ] **Decide a slug-drift strategy.** Either pin deliberately and accept periodic updates, or point at a stable alias if OpenRouter offers one. Document the choice in the README so future runs don't mystery-fail.

## 2. Robustness (forward-looking — it works, make it fail gracefully)

- [ ] **Adapter failure handling.** When one adversary errors (bad slug, network, auth), does the loop degrade gracefully — skip that adversary and continue — or abort the whole run? Confirm, and prefer "log + continue with remaining adversaries" so one dead agent doesn't kill a multi-round job.
- [ ] **Verdict parsing strictness.** Convergence depends on adversaries ending with `VERDICT: PASS` / `VERDICT: REVISE`. What happens if a model phrases it differently or omits it? Decide whether a missing verdict = REVISE (safe default) or an error, and make the parser explicit about it.
- [ ] **Round-limit + non-convergence reporting.** When the loop hits `--rounds` without unanimous PASS, the transcript should clearly mark it as *unconverged* (which adversaries still objected), not just stop. Confirm the transcript says so.

## 3. Reach / features (optional, only if you want to grow it)

- [ ] **A direct-SDK adapter.** README invites adding adapters to the `ADAPTERS` map (e.g. direct Anthropic/Gemini SDK calls) to skip OpenRouter. Build one if you want a non-OpenRouter path / lower latency.
- [ ] **`runs/` management.** Transcripts accumulate; consider a `.gitignore` for `runs/` (see §4) and/or an index of past runs if this becomes a regular tool.
- [ ] **Self-application.** This is literally an adversarial-review tool — worth pointing it at your *own* artifacts (e.g. a persona prompt, or the DE governance docs) as a red-team pass. Possible cross-pollination with the leak-harness's adversarial-co-evolution method.

## 4. Housekeeping

- [ ] **No `.gitignore` in the repo** (confirmed 404). Add one before things accumulate — at minimum `node_modules/`, `.env*`, and probably `runs/` (transcripts may contain task content you don't want public, since the repo is public). This is the one genuine hygiene gap.
- [ ] **Public repo, secrets check.** Clean so far (keys read from env: `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`, `GEMINI_API_KEY`, `OPENAI_API_KEY`). Just keep it that way — and the `.env*` gitignore above protects against an accidental local-key commit.

